","1348–1359":"1348–1359","1308–Male":"1308–Overleden","1308–Female":"1308–Overleden","1359":"1359","1348":"1348","about 1347":"circa 1347","about 1348":"circa 1348","1308":"1308","1328":"1328","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1328–":"1328–Deceased","1328–Female":"1328–Deceased","1328–Male":"1328–Deceased","1348–1359":"1348–1359","1308–Male":"1308–Deceased","1308–Female":"1308–Deceased","1359":"1359","1348":"1348","about 1347":"about 1347","about 1348":"about 1348","1308":"1308","1328":"1328","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Matham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Mattins Farm in Radwinter or Martinfield Green in Saffron Walden (both Essex).","2  English: locative name from Mathon (Worcs).","3  English: nickname possibly from Middle English  <i>mathme</i>,  <i>mathom</i> ‘treasure, precious gift’ (Old English  <i>māðm</i>,  <i>maððum</i>), though the early bearers cited here may rather belong to (1) or (2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Mattam","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Matham  ."]},{"name":"Matthams","meanings":["English: variant of   Matham   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Matham was born in 1328, her father, Hamelin Matham, was 20 and her mother, Cecily Lyons, was 20. She married John Mitchell about 1347, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1328–":"1328–Surnud","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","1328–Male":"1328–Surnud","1348–1359":"1348–1359","1308–Male